---
title: "What is AARM"
description: "A runtime security system that intercepts, evaluates, and enforces policy on AI-driven actions before they execute."
---

## Definition

**Autonomous Action Runtime Management (AARM)** is a system specification for securing AI-driven actions at runtime.
```
Agent ──► AARM ──► Tools
            │
            ▼
        Receipts
```

AARM sits between the agent and the tools it invokes. Every action flows through AARM before execution.

---

## What It Does

<Steps>
  <Step title="Intercept">
    Capture action requests before they reach tools
  </Step>
  <Step title="Evaluate">
    Check against policy: who, what, to where, in what context
  </Step>
  <Step title="Enforce">
    Allow, deny, modify, or require human approval
  </Step>
  <Step title="Record">
    Generate signed receipt for every action
  </Step>
</Steps>

---

## Core Principle

<Info>
The security boundary for AI agents is **tool execution**, not model outputs.
</Info>

You can't reliably control what an agent *thinks*. You can control what it *does*.

---

## Trust Model

| Component | Trust Level |
|-----------|-------------|
| AARM system | Trusted |
| Agent / LLM | Untrusted |
| User inputs | Untrusted |
| Tool outputs | Untrusted |

The agent isn't malicious—but it processes untrusted inputs. Treat it as potentially compromised.

---

## What AARM Is Not

- **Not a prompt filter** — operates on actions, not text
- **Not an observability tool** — prevents, not just observes
- **Not a specific product** — it's a specification

---

